					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Actually, DMC DMA may take less than 3 cycles if it lands on a CPU write. For example, if it lands on the dummy write in a RMW instruction, then the DMC will only be delayed by two cycles, after the effective write to the target address.
<br />
<br />An example, using opcode $6E (ROR - Absolute), followed by $AD (LDA - Absolute):
<br />
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">CYC INSTR&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;ACTION COMMENT<br />1&nbsp; &nbsp;ROR $0765 Read&nbsp; &nbsp;Fetch opcode<br />2&nbsp; &nbsp;ROR&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Read&nbsp; &nbsp;Fetch low address byte<br />3&nbsp; &nbsp;ROR&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Read&nbsp; &nbsp;Fetch high address byte<br />4&nbsp; &nbsp;ROR&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Write&nbsp; Dummy write&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;- DMC DMA lands here, RDY low cycle 1<br />5&nbsp; &nbsp;ROR&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Write&nbsp; Effective write &lt;- CPU is not paused here, RDY low cycle 2<br />1&nbsp; &nbsp;DMA&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; DMC DMA &#40;RDY low cycle 3 - CPU paused&#41;<br />2&nbsp; &nbsp;DMA&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; DMC DMA &#40;effective read from memory&#41;<br />1&nbsp; &nbsp;LDA $0300 Read&nbsp; &nbsp;Fetch opcode<br />....</div></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
